<paragraph blockId="9.[230,712,1258,1280]" box="[230,712,1258,1280]" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">
<heading box="[230,712,1258,1280]" centered="true" fontSize="9" level="2" pageId="9" pageNumber="706" reason="2">
<taxonomicName authority="THOMPSON, 1976" authorityName="Thompson" authorityYear="1976" box="[230,712,1258,1280]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="706" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittatum">
<emphasis box="[230,503,1258,1279]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">COPESTYLUM VITTATUM</emphasis>
THOMPSON, 1976
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[164,779,1296,1716]" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">
<emphasis box="[164,521,1296,1318]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">
Larva and puparium (
<figureCitation box="[428,507,1296,1318]" captionStart="Figures 20–22" captionStartId="41.[164,254,829,848]" captionTargetBox="[421,1184,197,797]" captionTargetId="figure-0@41.[419,1187,195,799]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="Figures 20–22. Third stage larval Copestylum, whole larva, head to the right; scale bar = 6 mm. 20, Copestylum satur; 21, Copestylum tetetzoi sp. nov.; 22, Copestylum vittatum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443492" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443492/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
):
</emphasis>
Anterior fold without extra large spicules. Anterior spiracles with three openings. Anterodorsal margin of mesothorax with groups of mostly broad setae and up to six spicules mostly in one row. Abdominal vestiture of long, upright setae. Anal lobe with pale, indistinct spicules. Vestiture between prolegs of fine not broad setae. Posterior breathing tube orange, not tapering. AP punctured, shiny, and as long as TR is wide (
<figureCitation box="[685,767,1541,1563]" captionStart="Figures 44–47" captionStartId="46.[144,234,1097,1116]" captionTargetBox="[303,1263,195,1067]" captionTargetId="figure-0@46.[303,1263,195,1067]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Figures 44–47. Puparia of Copestylum, scanning electron photomicrographs. 44, Copestylum florida, posterior breathing tube (prp), dorsal view width at TR = 0.3 mm; 45–47, Copestylum vittatum, 45, prp, apical view width 0.2 mm; 46, prp, dorsal view width at TR = 0.5mm; 47, pupal spiracles, whole view from above scale as indicated on images." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443506" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443506/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">Fig. 46</figureCitation>
). Posterior spiracular openings shaped as simple curves (
<figureCitation box="[253,334,1602,1624]" captionStart="Figures 44–47" captionStartId="46.[144,234,1097,1116]" captionTargetBox="[303,1263,195,1067]" captionTargetId="figure-0@46.[303,1263,195,1067]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Figures 44–47. Puparia of Copestylum, scanning electron photomicrographs. 44, Copestylum florida, posterior breathing tube (prp), dorsal view width at TR = 0.3 mm; 45–47, Copestylum vittatum, 45, prp, apical view width 0.2 mm; 46, prp, dorsal view width at TR = 0.5mm; 47, pupal spiracles, whole view from above scale as indicated on images." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443506" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443506/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">Fig. 45</figureCitation>
). Pupal spiracles orange, matt, shining apically, and with three encircling rings of openings in upper half (
<figureCitation box="[314,395,1663,1686]" captionStart="Figures 44–47" captionStartId="46.[144,234,1097,1116]" captionTargetBox="[303,1263,195,1067]" captionTargetId="figure-0@46.[303,1263,195,1067]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Figures 44–47. Puparia of Copestylum, scanning electron photomicrographs. 44, Copestylum florida, posterior breathing tube (prp), dorsal view width at TR = 0.3 mm; 45–47, Copestylum vittatum, 45, prp, apical view width 0.2 mm; 46, prp, dorsal view width at TR = 0.5mm; 47, pupal spiracles, whole view from above scale as indicated on images." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443506" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443506/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">Fig. 47</figureCitation>
). Pupal spiracles 1.7¥ as wide apart as a pupal spiracle is long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="706" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[164,779,1758,1903]" lastBlockId="9.[826,1442,198,373]" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">
<emphasis box="[164,619,1758,1780]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">
Taxonomic notes: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thompson" authorityYear="1976" box="[376,619,1758,1780]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="706" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittatum">Copestylum vittatum</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is similar to other members of the Pictum group that have nontapering posterior breathing tubes such as 
<taxonomicName box="[633,740,1820,1841]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="706" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="florida">
<emphasis box="[633,740,1820,1841]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">C. florida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Curran" baseAuthorityYear="1939" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="706" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pachecoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">C. pachecoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Marcos-García &amp; Hancock &amp; Pérez-Bañón &amp; Maier" authorityYear="2009" box="[330,486,1851,1872]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="706" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="santarosae">
<emphasis box="[330,486,1851,1872]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">C. santarosae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is distinguished from these species by the punctured AP (
<figureCitation box="[586,667,1881,1903]" captionStart="Figures 44–47" captionStartId="46.[144,234,1097,1116]" captionTargetBox="[303,1263,195,1067]" captionTargetId="figure-0@46.[303,1263,195,1067]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Figures 44–47. Puparia of Copestylum, scanning electron photomicrographs. 44, Copestylum florida, posterior breathing tube (prp), dorsal view width at TR = 0.3 mm; 45–47, Copestylum vittatum, 45, prp, apical view width 0.2 mm; 46, prp, dorsal view width at TR = 0.5mm; 47, pupal spiracles, whole view from above scale as indicated on images." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443506" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443506/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">Fig. 46</figureCitation>
), absence of broad setae between the prolegs, and only up to five spicules in one row on each side of the anterodorsal margin of the mesothorax. It is most similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="706" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="florida">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">C. florida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a punctured AP but differs from that species in having an AP that is as long as the width of the TR. In 
<taxonomicName box="[983,1092,351,372]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="706" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="florida">
<emphasis box="[983,1092,351,372]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="706">C. florida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the AP is longer than the TR.
</paragraph>
